# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The **1912 Triangular Tournament** was a Test cricket competition played between Australia, England and South Africa, the only Test-playing nations at the time.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The ultimate winners of the tournament were England, with four wins in their six matches, but the tournament was deemed a failure, with disappointing crowds and uncompetitive cricket, caused in part by a weakened Australia team.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was the first tournament in Test history to be played between more than two nations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] It was the only such tournament until the Asian Test Championships of 1998–99 and 2001–02, and the ICC World Test Championship which began in 2019.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a competition involving all three of the nations then playing Test cricket (Australia, England and South Africa) was proposed at the first meeting of the Imperial Cricket Conference in July 1909.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The original proposal was for a tournament to be held every four years, with the first hosted by England in 1912.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] For a variety of reasons, the tournament was not a success.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The summer was one of the wettest since records began in 1766: rainfall in the three months of June, July and August was more than twice the seasonal average, and August, 1912, was the coolest, dullest and wettest August of the 20th century.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] At that time, pitches were not covered to protect them against rain, so the batsmen were at a distinct disadvantage on the proverbial sticky wicket.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] These problems were exacerbated since Tests in England were in those days played over three days rather than the five days that is now usual.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] In addition, disputes between the players and management in Australia meant that six leading Australian players refused to tour whilst medical duties meant “Ranji” Hordern, easily Australia’s best bowler in the 1911–12 Ashes series, could not tour either.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] These setbacks severely weakened a team that had otherwise been level with England in recent Ashes series.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The leg spin and googly bowlers in the South African team were very effective on the matting pitches then in use in South Africa, but were less deadly on English grass pitches.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] As a result, England dominated, winning four of their six matches and drawing the other two.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was so unsuccessful that it has never been repeated.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a tournament of international cricket matches between more than two countries was not repeated, outside of regional tournaments in East Africa and the West Indies, until the invention of One Day International cricket and the first Women's Cricket World Cup in 1973.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] The only other Test cricket tournaments in history were the Asian Test Championships played in 1998–99 and 2001–02, which were also not great successes, until the ICC World Test Championship began in 2019.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1912-triangular-tournament] Perhaps the most notable incident of the series was Australian bowler Jimmy Matthews taking two hat-tricks in the same Test match, one in each innings of the opening match against South Africa, the only time a bowler has taken two hat-tricks in the same Test.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The **1979 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '79**) was the second edition of the Cricket World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference, it was held in England from 9 to 23 June 1979.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was once again sponsored by the Prudential Assurance Company and had eight teams participating in the tournament with the only change being Canada who qualified with Sri Lanka in the qualifier for the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The format remained the same with two teams qualifying from each group with the final once again being at Lord's.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] England joined first-time semi-finalists Pakistan as the qualifiers from Group A, while the West Indies finished top of Group B ahead of New Zealand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] After the West Indies and England both won their semi-finals over Pakistan and New Zealand, respectively, they met in the final at Lord's with the West Indies defending their title from four years earlier with a 92-run victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] West Indian batsman, Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs from four matches with English player Mike Hendrick ending up as the leading wicket-taker with ten wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The eight teams at the tournament were split into two groups of four teams, with each team playing the others in their group in a single round-robin format.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group then advance to the semi-finals to play in a single-elimination tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 tournament saw the first qualifiers in a World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 ICC Trophy was held during late May and early June at various grounds in the English Midlands, with the two finalists qualifying for the World Cup where they joined the six Test nations who qualified automatically.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Sri Lanka and Canada qualified after defeating Denmark and Bermuda respectively in the semi-finals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 9 June with four matches being played.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] England took on Australia at Lord's and after the home team elected to field first, restricted the Australians to 97 for one with fine fielding and bowling.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] After Andrew Hilditch dragged his second ball after lunch into the stumps, the Australians would be restricted for 159 which included four run-outs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The run-chase saw Mike Brearley and Graham Gooch control the innings and led England to a six wicket victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] In a very close semi-final match, England prevailed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] England began badly, falling to 38/2, before Mike Brearley (53 from 115 balls, 3 fours) and Graham Gooch (71 from 84 balls, 1 four, 3 sixes) resurrected the innings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Derek Randall (42 from 50 balls, 1 four, 1 six) played well in the second half of the innings, as England recovered from 98/4 to post 221 (8 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] In the response, John Wright (69 from 137 balls) attacked well in the beginning.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of wickets bogged New Zealand down, and despite several late flourishes in the batting order, New Zealand started to drop behind.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] When New Zealand could not achieve the remaining 14 runs from the last over of the match, England went into the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge (73 from 107 balls, 5 fours, 1 six) and Desmond Haynes (65 from 115 balls, 4 fours) set a first wicket partnership of 132 runs in a match dominated by batting.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and Clive Lloyd also contributed solidly, as West Indies ran up 293 (6 wickets, 60 overs) against Pakistan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Majid Khan (81 from 124 balls, 7 fours) and Zaheer Abbas (93 from 122 balls) shared a second-wicket partnership of 166 runs in 36 overs in the response.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, none of the other Pakistani batsmen flourished, with Javed Miandad being bowled for a duck first ball, and Pakistan lost 9/74, beginning with the dismissal of Abbas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan was bowled out for 250 in 56.2 overs in the high-scoring semi-final, sending the West Indies to the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] England won the toss and chose to field first.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies got off to a bad start, falling to 99/4 with the loss of Greenidge, Haynes, Kallicharan, and captain Clive Lloyd.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, Vivian Richards (138 from 157 balls, 11 fours, 3 sixes) and Collis King (86 from 66 balls, 10 fours, 3 sixes) consolidated the innings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] King especially savaged the English bowling, with a strike rate of 130.3.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies were 238/5 when the 139 run partnership ended with King’s dismissal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and the tail then took the West Indies to a very imposing total of 286 (9 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The English batsmen got off to a good start.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] But the openers, Mike Brearley (64 from 130 balls, 7 fours) and Geoff Boycott (57 from 105 balls, 3 fours) scored very slowly with a methodical opening partnership of 129 runs in 38 overs, playing as if the match were a five-day Test.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] By the time both batsmen were out, the required run rate had risen too high, putting pressure on the later batsmen.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch played some hefty strokes in scoring his 32, taking England to 183/2.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of Derek Randall triggered a batting collapse in which England lost their last eight wickets for 11 runs to finish all out for 194 in 51 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards was declared Man of the Match.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs coming from his four games.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Second was fellow West Indian player, Viv Richards who finished with 217 runs from four games which included the highest individual score of the tournament of 138 in the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch from England rounded out the top three.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] Mike Hendrick from England was the leading wicket taker for the tournament with ten wickets from five matches with a three-way tie for second place with Brian McKechnie (New Zealand), Asif Iqbal (Pakistan) and Chris Old each taking nine wickets for the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-cricket-world-cup] The total attendance at the tournament was 132,000, including 25,000 at the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The **1979 ICC Trophy** was a limited overs cricket tournament held in England between 22 May and 21 June 1979.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] It was the inaugural ICC Trophy tournament to be staged, with matches between the 15 participating teams played over 60 overs a team and with white clothing and red balls.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] All matches were played in the Midlands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The tournament served as the Cricket World Cup qualification process – the two finalists, Sri Lanka and Canada, qualified to take part in the 1979 World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The World Cup began on 9 June, just three days after Sri Lanka and Canada qualified for it by winning their ICC Trophy semi-finals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The ICC Trophy final was held on 21 June at Worcestershire's ground at New Road, two days before the World Cup final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] Sri Lanka won the first ICC Trophy defeating Canada by 60 runs in the final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] East Africa who played in the first World Cup did not qualify this time, which meant there would be no nation from the African region participating in the 1979 World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The 15 teams were divided into three groups of five.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] Each team played each other team in its group once in matches played between 22 May and 4 June, scoring four points for a win and two for a no-result (match started but not finished) or abandoned entirely without a ball being bowled.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The three group winners and the team with the fourth-highest points total after the group stage went forward to the semi-finals, the top team playing the fourth-ranked team and the team with the second-highest number of points playing the third.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] Where teams finished with equal points totals, run rate was used to separate them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The top five run scorers (total runs) are included in this table.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1979-icc-trophy] The top five wicket takers are listed in this table, listed by wickets taken and then by bowling average.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The **1982 ICC Trophy** was a limited-overs cricket tournament held in England between 16 June and 10 July 1982.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] It was the second ICC Trophy tournament to be staged, with matches between the 16 participating teams played over 60 overs a team and with white clothing and red balls.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] As in the 1979 tournament, all matches were played in the Midlands, though on this occasion the final was held at Grace Road, Leicester.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The tournament served as the Cricket World Cup qualification process – Zimbabwe, who didn't play in the first tournament, defeated Bermuda in the final to qualify for the 1983 World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Bad weather hampered the tournament throughout, with many games called off early or abandoned entirely because of rain; West Africa suffered the most, seeing a result in only two of their seven group matches.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Sri Lanka, who won the first tournament in 1979, had by now been promoted to Full Test and ODI status, and so did not take part, and automatically qualified for the World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] As a result only one spot was on offer to join the seven Full members in the World Cup which was won by Zimbabwe.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The 16 teams were divided into two groups of eight.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Each teams played each other team in its group once in matches played between 16 June and 5 July, scoring four points for a win and two for a no-result (match started but not finished) or abandoned entirely without a ball being bowled.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The top two teams in each group went forward to the semi-finals, the top team (With the highest number of points) in one group playing the runner-up from the other group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Where teams finished with equal points totals, first the number of games won and secondly run rate was used to separate them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Kenya recorded an easy nine-wicket win over Gibraltar.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The Europeans were dismissed for just 80 (RCR Patel 3-13) and their opponents rushed to victory in 14.2 overs, with Rehmann making 53 not out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] In a low-scoring match, Papua New Guinea beat Hong Kong by four wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The young Dermot Reeve made 38 for Hong Kong and took 2-26, but the Papuans overhauled their target of 100 with 34.4 overs in hand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Elsewhere, Zimbabwe crushed the USA by 191 runs, thanks to a second-wicket partnership of 214 between David Houghton (135) and Kevin Curran (126 not out) that set them on their way to 332/4.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The Americans were never remotely in the hunt, and 4-34 from Peter Rawson restricted their total to just 141.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Gibraltar were in trouble at 42/4 against the United States, Shamshad Durrani having taken 3-12, before the rains came and put paid to any chance of a result.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] In a match reduced to 45 overs a team, Hong Kong's 207/7 (Andy Lorimer 53) was good enough, though Nissam Reuben's 6-2-7-3 was noteworthy, and the Israelis collapsed to 84 all out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] In an all-African affair reduced to a 25-over game, Zimbabwe posted a highly competitive 192/4 (Houghton 71, Jack Heron 50) which Kenya never got anywhere near, making just 72/4 to lose by 120 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The game between Gibraltar and Zimbabwe saw no play at all, and nor did the matches between Kenya and the USA or between Canada and Hong Kong.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The other game did produce a result, however, with Israel recovering from the depths of 32/5 to post a reasonable-looking 167/9, bolstered by 75 not out from Stanley Perlman.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Despite losing an early wicket, however, the Papuans cantered to a nine-wicket win as Nigel Robert Agonia (86 not out) and Taunao Vai (75 not out) added an unbroken 157 for the second wicket.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Israel were in dire straits at 74/6 against Kenya when the weather intervened, but that was the only action on this day, with Canada v Gibraltar and Papua New Guinea v the USA seeing not a ball bowled between them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Yet another rain-affected day saw no match reach a positive result.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Canada had made 8/0 from nine overs against Zimbabwe when the players left the field, while Gibraltar reached 42/2 against Israel from ten.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] There was no play at all between Hong Kong and the United States.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] At last the weather held off for long enough to allow all three matches to reach a conclusion, albeit from a reduced number of overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] In a 55-over game, Papua New Guinea won against the odds by 30 runs against Canada, an unbeaten 101 from Vavine Pala guiding them to 231/7 from 83/6 while K Kalo took 4-26 as the Canadians could manage only 211 despite 50 from Tariq Javed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Gibraltar's 129/8 off 40 overs (Gordon Bacon 4-37) proved well short of what was required, as Des Greenwood and Reeve both made unbeaten scores of 56 to guide Hong Kong to an eight-wicket triumph.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Finally, Israel slumped to 65 all out against Zimbabwe, with only Perlman reaching double figures and John Traicos taking 4-22.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] In reply the Africans scorched to a nine-wicket victory from a mere 7.3 overs, Houghton making 43.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The North American derby produced a comprehensive 138-run win for Canada, who compiled 233 (Tariq Javed 68) before captain RJ Stevens took 4-26 as the USA could manage just 95 all out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Hong Kong dived to 47/7 before recovering to 105, but 39 not out from Hitesh Mehta saw Kenya home by three wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Finally, Papua New Guinea could manage only 94 in their game against Zimbabwe, and Houghton (44 not out) and Curran (30 not out) ensured a simple nine-wicket victory for the African team.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] An innings of 107 by IF Kirmani enabled Canada to make 242/8 against Kenya, and despite 53 from GA Musa 4-26 from Clement Neblett meant that the Africans fell 45 runs short.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Gibraltar made a mere 55, the lowest total of the tournament, against Papua New Guinea with Pala taking 4-30, and the Papuans made short work of their target as they cruised to a nine-wicket win.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Against the United States, Israel made a creditable 157, but NS Lashkari (76 not out) and Kamran Rasheed (65 not out) guided the Americans to a comfortable eight-wicket triumph.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Canada won by a walk-over after Israel were unable to field a team due to a dispute between the players and management, but the teams decided to play a friendly match the following morning, which the Canadians won by three wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Elsewhere, 72 not out from Andy Lorimer contributed to a Hong Kong total of 192/4, which proved insufficient against Zimbabwe as their opponents won by seven wickets, future Test player Andy Pycroft hitting 83 not out and Heron 51.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Kenya's total of 210/8 (Mehta 52) was too much for Papua New Guinea, for whom W Maha with 61 was the only man to pass 32; the Papuans were bowled out for 173 to lose by 37 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Despite having five men run out, Bangladesh compiled 246 (Gazi Ashraf 77) against West Africa, and this proved more than enough as their opponents fell to 96/7 before a late-innings rally from S Elliott (38) restored some respectability to leave them 76 runs short on 170/9.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] A hopelessly one-sided game saw Bermuda amass 348/9 against Malaysia, with Gladstone Brown (100) and Winston Reid (128) sharing an opening stand of 211.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] In reply, Banerji made a brave 34 but none of his team-mates reached double figures as the Malaysians were rolled over for just 64 to lose by 284 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Elvin James recorded astonishing bowling figures of 7.1-5-2-5 for Bermuda.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] And the Netherlands' 150/8 was sufficient to hold off East Africa (127) in a match that produced no fewer than 52 extras between the two teams.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Rain destroyed any chance of meaningful play on this day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The matches between East Africa and Singapore and between the Netherlands and West Africa were abandoned without a ball being bowled, while the one game that did get underway saw Fiji reach 31/2 off 14 overs before a halt was called to proceedings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The match between the Netherlands and Singapore was abandoned with no play possible, but the other two games produced results.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh were restricted to 143 against East Africa thanks to William Bourne's 4-33, but no-one but Extras passed 20 in reply and Bangladesh won by 26 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Elsewhere, in a game reduced to a 20-over thrash, Bermuda's 153/5 (captain Colin Blades 45 not out) proved too much for Fiji, who could manage only 102/6 to lose by 51 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] All three matches scheduled for this day - Bangladesh v Singapore, East Africa v Malaysia and Fiji v West Africa - were abandoned without a ball being bowled.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The weather proved the only winner once more, as again all three games - Bangladesh v Fiji, Bermuda v the Netherlands and Singapore v West Africa - saw no play whatsoever.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The most exciting of the four games scheduled for this day was a thrilling one-run victory in a 25-over match by Bangladesh over Malaysia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Raqibul Hasan made 35 in the Bangladeshi's 122/7, but Malaysia were closing on their target at 113/4 before two quick wickets fell; they ended just short on 121/6.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Bermuda (116/4) beat Singapore (115) by six wickets thanks to 48 from Noel Gibbons after Winston Trott had claimed 4-27.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Rain stopped play when Fiji were 79/2 in reply to the Netherlands' imposing 251/6, RJ Elferink hitting a fine 154 not out, but the Dutch had done enough to win on faster scoring rate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The East-West Africa clash was a disappointment, however, being called off after East Africa had reached 53/2 from 25.1 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh had a game to forget against Bermuda, being bowled out for 67 with only Nazim Shirazi reaching double figures as Lionel Thomas took 4-13.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The Bermudians lost three wickets in reply, but were never really in trouble as they reached their target from 15.5 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] An opening stand of 94 between KW Arnold (54) and DC Patel (52) laid the foundations for East Africa's 220/7 against Fiji, and 4-21 from Desai made sure of an 88-run victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Malaysia put up 128 in an all-south-east-Asian clash with Singapore, but their opponents glided to a six-wicket win with more than 15 overs to spate thanks to a knock of 67 from FJR Martens.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh (167/4) beat the Netherlands (163) by six wickets in a match that saw no outstanding individual performances, the highest score Yousuf Rahman's 45.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Scores of 68 from Thomas and 51 from Allan Douglas helped Bermuda to 240 in a 56-over game, and despite 64 from DC Patel, East Africa could manage no more than 176, 64 runs adrift.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Finally, there was no result in the game between Malaysia and West Africa, the Malaysians having made 219/9 from 58 overs (S Elliott 75, J Onyechi 57; K Kamalanathan 4-45) when the players were forced from the field.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] West Africa batted well against Bermuda to post a total of 249, with Elliott making 67 and Onyechi 53 despite Elvin James' 4-41.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] An unbroken partnership of 125 between Brown (78 not out) and Blades (82 not out) settled the matter, however, as the Bermudians won by seven wickets with more than 11 overs in hand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] M Rajalingham took 5-39 for Singapore to restrict Fiji to 219, but it was not quite enough as the Singaporeans were bowled out 14 runs short for 205.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Batting first, Bangladesh stuttered to 45/4, and a fifth-wicket stand of 52 was in vain as 4-31 from Kevin Curran restricted the team to an inadequate 124.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] David Houghton fell for 1 in the Zimbabwean reply, but once Heron (63 not out) and Curran (44) had added 103 for the second wicket there was only one winner, and they reached their target with more than 30 overs to spare to record an easy eight-wicket victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Papua New Guinea were in all sorts of trouble after collapsing to 48/6, but Pala stopped the rot with 72 and they eventually reached 153 before being bowled out in 39 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Despite losing Brown before a run had been scored, Bermuda ran out six-wicket winners despite losing three wickets for four runs at one stage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Blades hit 69 not out in an unbeaten hundred partnership with John Tucker.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Bangladesh put up a total of 224, thanks largely to an excellent 115 by Yousuf Rahman and 52 by Nazim Shirazi.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] From the commanding heights of 170/0, though, they lost all ten wickets for 54 runs (and their last six for 16) as La'a Aukopi returned outstanding figures of 5-14 from 11 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] The Papuans were inspired by this to reach their target with three wickets and three overs remaining, W Maha hitting 60 in a three-wicket victory despite Bangladeshi captain and wicket-keeper Shafiq-ul-Haq making three stumpings in the innings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] No batsman reached 50 in the Bermudian innings, but solid contributions from Brown (48), Blades (45) and Douglas (36) guided them to a reasonable 231/8 from their 60 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Duncan Fletcher was the pick of the Zimbabwean bowlers with 3-34 from nine overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1982-icc-trophy] Zimbabwe looked in a spot of bother at 30/2 with both openers gone, but the match and the Trophy were decided by half-centuries from Andy Pycroft, who made 82, and Craig Hodgson (57 not out); the Africans won with more than five overs to spare.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The **1983 Cricket World Cup** (officially the **Prudential Cup '83**) was the third edition of the Cricket World Cup tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] It was held from 9 to 25 June 1983 in England and Wales and was won by India.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Eight countries participated in the event.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] England, India, Pakistan and West Indies qualified for the semi-finals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The preliminary matches were played in two groups of four teams each, and each country played the others in its group twice.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams in each group qualified for the semi-finals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The matches consisted of 60 overs per innings and were played in traditional white clothing and with red balls.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The eight teams at the tournament were divided into two groups of four, and each team would play the others in their group twice.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group then advanced to the semi-finals, which were played as a single-elimination tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Every game was 60 overs a team, and there were no day/night matches.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams qualified for the final tournament (seven full ICC members, including recently appointed full member Sri Lanka, and Zimbabwe, who qualified by winning the 1982 ICC Trophy).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Unlike in previous Cricket World Cups, the group stages were played in a double round robin format.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Group A comprised the hosts England, Pakistan, New Zealand and Sri Lanka; while Group B contained reigning champions West Indies, India, Australia, and the sole qualifier Zimbabwe.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Unlike in later World Cups, with formats designed such that all games could be screened live on television, matches took place simultaneously at multiple venues, with matches played every other day and a reserve day in case of rain, although only three of the matches required a second day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, England started strongly with a 106 run victory over New Zealand at The Oval, scoring an imposing 322/6 in their innings, driven by a partnership of 115 in 16 overs between Allan Lamb and Mike Gatting.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan also started with a win, by 50 runs over Sri Lanka, despite being hampered throughout the tournament by Imran Khan being unfit to bowl, after scoring 338/5 in 60 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] England's second group match brought a second win, as David Gower's 130, including five sixes and 12 fours, powered a 47 run win over Sri Lanka.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Meanwhile, New Zealand beat Pakistan by 52 runs despite Abdul Qadir's 4/21 in 12 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] England then beat Pakistan by 8 wickets with nearly ten overs to spare at Lord's, while Richard Hadlee's 5/25 saw Sri Lanka bowled out for 206, New Zealand getting home with over 20 overs to spare.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] England's only defeat of the group stages came in the fourth round of matches, against New Zealand, off the penultimate ball of the New Zealand innings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan triumphed over Sri Lanka, once again led by Abdul Qadir (5/44).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The fifth round of matches on 18 June saw England seal their place in the semi-final, with a first wicket partnership of 115 between Graeme Fowler and Chris Tavaré alone scoring nearly half of Pakistan's 232.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Meanwhile, New Zealand failed to secure passage to the knockout stage, losing to Sri Lanka in a low scoring affair.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the final round of matches, England beat Sri Lanka by 9 wickets in a match with no implications for the final table.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The match between New Zealand and Pakistan would decide the second qualifier.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Any win by New Zealand would be sufficient to see them qualify; Pakistan had not only to win, but do so by a sufficient margin to overhaul New Zealand's average run rate.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] An 11 run victory for Pakistan proved sufficient, as Zaheer Abbas made an unbeaten 103 before New Zealand were bowled out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Group B started with the first shock of the tournament, as Zimbabwe beat Australia in what Wisden described as "a bigger surprise than any in the previous two world cups".
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Duncan Fletcher led the way, making 69* and being awarded man of the match.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Wet weather in the second round of games played on 11 June led to low scores.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] West Indies scored 252/9 in their innings, which stretched over two days, against Australia; in response, Australia were bowled out for 151 in just 30.3 overs, an effort not helped by Graeme Wood being taken to hospital with severe concussion after being hit by Michael Holding.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] India comfortably beat Zimbabwe by 5 wickets in the contemporaneous fixture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Two days later, Australia defeated India by 162 runs, with man of the match Trevor Chappell scoring 110 off 131 balls and Ken MacLeay taking 6/39.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The other match that day was also a one-sided affair, as West Indies restricted Zimbabwe to just 217/7 in their 60 overs, despite Duncan Fletcher scoring another unbeaten half century, and then romped home with a partnership of 195 for the third wicket between Gordon Greenidge and Larry Gomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the first of the return fixtures, West Indies overcame India by 66 runs, with Viv Richards making 119; for the second time in the tournament, an opposing batsman retired hurt, as Dilip Vengsarkar was the unlucky batsman on this occasion, hit in the mouth by Malcolm Marshall.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Australia beat Zimbabwe by 32 runs to level their account in the tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] West Indies qualified for the semi-finals with a match to spare, beating Australia by 7 wickets substantially due to a partnership of 124 for the second wicket between Greenidge and Richards.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] That left West Indies versus Zimbabwe as a dead rubber, and West Indies duly won by ten wickets with nearly fifteen overs to spare.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The final group B match was a straightforward tussle for qualification between Australia and India.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] However, after India had made 247 all out, in a team effort where the highest score was 40 and there were 37 extras, Australia collapsed to 129 all out, with Madan Lal and Roger Binny taking four wickets each.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the first semi-final, at Old Trafford on 22 June, England won the toss and elected to bat.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The English batsmen mistimed many balls and used the bat's edge frequently, as the restrictive Indian bowling led England to score 213 (all out, 60 overs).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Graeme Fowler (33 from 59 balls, 3 fours) top scored, and Kapil Dev took 3 for 35 in eleven overs, with Mohinder Amarnath and Roger Binny taking two wickets each.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] In reply, Yashpal Sharma (61 from 115 balls, 3 fours, 2 sixes) and Sandeep Patil (51 from 32 balls, 8 fours) made half-centuries, as India reached their target in 54.4 overs, winning by 6 wickets in a classic victory over the previous tournament's runners-up.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Mohinder Amarnath (46 from 92 balls, 4 fours, 1 six) picked up the man-of-the-match award for his all round performance, which saw him add 46 runs to his earlier bowling success (2/27 in 12 overs).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final, between Pakistan and the West Indies, was staged at The Oval on the same day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] West Indies won the toss and invited Pakistan to bat, whom they restricted to just 184 (8 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Mohsin Khan (70 from 176 balls, 1 four) fought his way past 50 against the formidable West Indies bowling attack (he was the only Pakistani batsman to reach 50).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Malcolm Marshall (3/28) and Andy Roberts (2/25) starred with the ball.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] In the final, India lost the toss and were asked to bat first against the West Indies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Only Krishnamachari Srikkanth (38 from 57 balls) and Mohinder Amarnath (26 from 80 balls) put up any significant resistance as Roberts, Marshall, Joel Garner and Michael Holding ripped through the Indian batsmen, ably supported by Gomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Surprising resistance by the tail allowed India to compile 183 (all out, 54.4 overs).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Sandeep Patil and Madan Lal saved the game to get the team past the 150-run mark at a critical point in the match where India scored 183 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Without those two batsmen, India's score would have been lower.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] The Indian bowling exploited the weather and pitch conditions perfectly to bowl out the West Indies for 140 from 52 overs, winning by 43 runs and completing one of the most stunning upsets in cricket history.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] It still remains the lowest ever total successfully defended in a World Cup final.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Amarnath and Madan Lal each took three wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Viv Richards, was West Indies' top scorer with 33 from 28 balls.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Kant was the most economical bowler, conceding 0 runs from his two overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] Amarnath was once again awarded the Man of the Match award for his all-round performance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1983-cricket-world-cup] There was no 'Man of the Series' awarded in 1983.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The **1986 ICC Trophy** was a limited-overs cricket tournament held in England between 11 June and 7 July 1986.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] It was the third ICC Trophy tournament to be staged, and as with the previous two tournaments, games between the 16 participating teams were played over 60 overs a team and with white clothing and red balls.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] All matches except the final were played in the Midlands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The tournament served as the Cricket World Cup qualification process – Zimbabwe defeated the Netherlands to win their second ICC Trophy in a row and qualify for the 1987 World Cup.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The weather was much better than the earlier competitions, and all matches were played to a result.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The 16 teams were divided into two groups, one containing seven teams and the other containing nine.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The top two teams in each group went forward to the semi-finals, the top team in each group playing team with the runner-up from the other.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In a match reduced to 50 overs a team, Denmark (221/7) easily defeated Argentina (100).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Soren Henriksen made 56 for the Danes, while Ole Mortensen took 4-15.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] A fine knock of 135 by Andy Pycroft helped Zimbabwe to pile up 315/7 against Bangladesh who could manage only 171/8 in reply (Malcolm Jarvis 4-28).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Meanwhile, 56 from P Banerji and 4-27 from DP John got Malaysia (142/8) through to a tight two-wicket victory over East Africa (140), despite DM Patel claiming 4-19.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] 58 from P Budin helped Malaysia to 226/9, but the real culprits were the Argentine bowlers, who sent down a staggering 26 wides in the innings; AH Gooding took 4-35 from six overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply Argentina fell to 44/7 and DA Culley's 41 could do no more than delay the inevitable as they were bowled out for 88 to lose by 134 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The other match played on this date was much closer, Bangladesh successfully defending a small total of 143 (Minhajul Abedin 50) by bowling out Kenya for 134.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Denmark recovered from 20/2 to post a total of 274/7, with S Mikkelsen making 60, Ole Mortensen 59 and Soren Henriksen 50.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply, East Africa could manage only 161, to lose by the large margin of 113 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Some excellent Zimbabwean bowling (Peter Rawson 9-3-16-3, John Traicos 10-2-19-3) saw them dismiss Kenya for 82, cruising to a seven-wicket triumph with more than half their overs remaining.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Argentina surprisingly reduced Zimbabwe to 98/5, but then a stand of 174 between Rawson (125) and Gary Wallace (77) saw the Africans through to a daunting 357/7.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Argentina were never likely to threaten such a target, and so it proved as they were bowled out for 150 to lose by a massive 207 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In the other Group A game, Jahangir Shah took 4-37 for Bangladesh but could not stop Malaysia making 239 (Asgari Stevens 68, Yazid Imran 64); DP John took 5-40 as the Bangladeshis slid to a 57-run defeat despite Rafiqul Alam's 51.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Bangladesh made 162 against East Africa, with SM Lakha taking 4-31.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply their opponents reached their target with only four wickets down, thanks largely to a stand of 125 for the third wicket between BR Bouri (66 not out) and FG Patel (53).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] 4-21 from England's future nemesis Eddo Brandes restricted Denmark to 146, a total which the Zimbabweans cruised past inside 35 overs, Grant Paterson making 86 not out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] And 66 from Stevens helped Malaysia to 154, but it was insufficient as Kenya, 99/5 at one stage, recovered to win by five wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Despite no player reaching fifty, East Africa's 261/8 was always likely to be too good for Argentina, and so it proved as the South Americans were dismissed 84 runs short for 177, A Kumar claiming 6-26.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The other match on this day, playing in Leicestershire at Egerton Park, saw Malaysia bowled out for 89 by Zimbabwe (Brandes 4-13, Rawson 4-22) who reached their target with little drama for the loss of just two wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Extras top-scored with 29 in Argentina's poor total of 122 against Bangladesh; the Asians had no problem knocking off the runs, Raqibul Hasan hitting 47 not out as they glided to an eight-wicket victory with more than 20 overs in hand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] An exciting second match saw Denmark overcome Kenya by one wicket: some tight bowling from Mortensen (3-23) had restricted the Kenyans to 121, and although Denmark fell to 96/9, an unbroken last-wicket stand of 26 saw them through.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] For East Africa, GR Shariff made 72 and BR Bouri 31, but no one else passed 7 as Brandes (5-37) wreaked havoc to dismiss them for 140.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply, Zimbabwe reached 143/0 with 33 overs to spare, with David Houghton scoring 87 not out and Paterson 55 not out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Anil Patel made 65 out of Kenya's 209/9 against local rivals East Africa, who had no chance once they had slumped to 33/5 and lost in the end by 63 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Kenya's captain Tom Tikolo top-scored with 48 as the Africans reached 228 all out against Argentina, who were unable to cope with the bowling of Zahoor Sheikh (4-25) and could do no better than 141, thus losing by 87 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Nehal Hasnain's 56 stood out for Bangladesh as Mortensen's 4-31 prevented their getting beyond 147; 49 for Johnny Jensen ensured a four-wicket victory for the Danes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] A completely one-sided match saw Bermuda amass 304/9 (Arnold Manders 75) and then bowl out Fiji for just 69, with two men bowling unchanged throughout: A Edwards took 6-38 while T Burgess claimed 4-29.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The USA's total of 152 looked vulnerable as Derek Abraham picked up 4-27, but Canada collapsed in reply and were dismissed for 79, Kamran Rasheed taking 4-22.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] An ICC Trophy record 172 from Simon Myles, who put on 174 for the third wicket with Nigel Stearns (62) guided Hong Kong to 324/5, and 63 from Gibraltar's Gary De'Ath made no difference to the result as they finished on 180/5, 144 runs adrift.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The Netherlands won another one-sided game as they made 271/6 (RE Lifmann 98, RJ Elferink 64) and then ran through Papua New Guinea's batting, Paul-Jan Bakker taking 5-18 as PNG were bowled out for a mere 52.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Bermuda became the first team to pass 400 in the ICC Trophy as they flayed Hong Kong's bowlers to the tune of 407/8, with Noel Gibbons making 125 not out and Ricky Hill 84, though Bob Fotheringham did take 4-51.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Martin Sabine top-scored for Hong Kong with 55, but they fell 227 runs short of their target on 180/6.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Canada made a reasonable 225/6 against the Netherlands (D Singh 50), but the Dutch recorded a six-wicket win with three overs to spare thanks to Rupert Gomes (82) and Steven Lubbers (51).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] D Moss made 108 for Israel against Fiji, but the next highest score was Extras with 19 and they totalled a disappointing 155 (Apenisa Waqaninamata 4-24) and 68 not out from VSJ Campbell set Fiji on their way to a nine-wicket victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Kamran Rasheed made 73 and NS Lashkari 50 as the USA (283/7) beat Papua New Guinea (234; Karo Ao 62) by 49 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Outstanding figures of 10-6-10-4 from Bermuda's T Burgess kept Israel's total down to a measly 86, and Winston Reid plundered 63 not out as the Bermudians raced to their target in under 14 overs for the loss of just one wicket.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Paul Prashad hit an unbeaten 164 for Canada as they made their way to 356/6, ably supported by D Singh (65).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Papua New Guinea showed fight in their response, Karo Ao (67) and Taunao Vai (51) compiling an opening stand of 126, but then F Waithe (4-37) reduced them to 133/4 and there was no way back; Derick Etwaroo took 4-64 and PNG ended on 267/9.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] FA Cup hero Tim Buzaglo made 88 for Gibraltar as they reached 185/8, but 55 from E Vakausausa made sure of victory for Fiji (187/4).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] And Bakker took 5-20 as the USA slid to 88 all out and a ten-wicket loss to the Netherlands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Bermuda made 224/9 (Hill 58, Manders 56), but despite no-one reaching 50 most of the USA team chipped in with useful runs and they won by three wickets with 16 balls to spare.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] 87 from Stearns and 80 from Myles helped Hong Kong to a good 261/7 against Canada, but a century opening partnership between Omadat Dipchand (76) and Prashad (40), plus 51 from IF Kirmani, got them to their target with four wickets and three balls remaining.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Papua New Guinea obliterated Gibraltar by the little matter of 369 runs, amassing a Trophy record 455/9 (B Harry 127, Charles Amini 97, Api Leka 69, Renagi Ila 60 not out).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] De'Ath took five wickets, but his 12 overs cost 88 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply Gibraltar had no chance, subsiding to 86 all out with Maha taking 5-12 and G Ravu 4-16.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Another lop-sided game saw the Netherlands put on 251 for the first wicket against Israel, Steve Atkinson making 162 and Lifmann 110.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Gomes added 64 not out and Lubbers 50 as the Dutch closed on 425/4.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] D Moss made 62 and Stanley Perlman 51 for Israel as they reached 111/1, but that was as good as it got: Elferink ran through the order with 6-22 and they lost by 267 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Gibraltar were humiliated by Canada: Abraham took 5-9 as the Gibraltarians were dismissed for 46, the lowest total of the tournament, and it could have been worse as they were 17/7 at one point.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply the Canadians smashed 48 from just 23 balls to record the easiest of ten-wicket wins.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] CAC Browne made 57 as Fiji posted a competitive total of 251 against the United States, but an unbeaten 104 by Lashkari and 74 from Kamran Rasheed ensured a five-wicket win for the Americans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The Dutch put on 200 for the second wicket against Hong Kong (Atkinson 107, Gomes 101) and their opponents could only manage 157/9 from their allotted overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Finally, Harry made 162 and Maha 52 as Papua New Guinea (377/6) destroyed Israel (100); Amini took 5-19 for the Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Gibraltar's 143/7 included 33 extras, but Bermuda still recorded a comfortable seven-wicket win.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Canada made their way to 328/7 against Israel, with 120 from Prashad the highlight and support from captain Clement Neblett (63) and IF Kirmani (57).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Their opponents could manage only 94 in reply (D Singh 4-34).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Papua New Guinea beat Fiji by 195 runs, PNG's 381/8 boosted by 113 from W Maha; N Tiana claimed 4-50 in Fiji's innings as they were bowled out for 186.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] And despite Chris Collins' 53 pulling Hong Kong up from 58/6 to 143 all out, the USA secured a five-wicket win inside 25 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] 4-18 from Gibbons kept Canada's total down to an unimpressive 119 against Bermuda; the islanders reached their target for the loss of only two wickets, with S Lightbourne making an unbeaten 70.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] An outstanding analysis of 10.3-3-14-6 by the Netherlands' RJ Elferink helped them to dismiss Fiji for 103, and then Steve Atkinson contributed 52 not out towards a nine-wicket win for the Dutch.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] MU Prabhudas' 5-23 for the United States against Gibraltar restricted the latter to 136; the Americans won by eight wickets with captain and former West Indies Test batsman Sew Shivnarine making 70 not out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Papua New Guinea subsided to 48/6 before 73 from number eight batsman Raki Ila restored some respectability; nevertheless their final total of 184 was not enough, 65 from opener Ricky Hill setting Bermuda on their way to a six-wicket triumph.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] 6-11 from slow left-armer Bharat Gohel resulted in Fiji's dismissal for a paltry 87 against Hong Kong, who won by seven wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Gibraltar were all out for 134 against the Dutch, who then launched an astonishing assault against the Gibraltarian bowling, reaching 137/2 from just 11 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Against Israel, the United States ran up 396/4 (Kamran Rasheed 143 not out, H Blackman 83, Shivnarine 66, K Lorick 50 not out) before Prabhudas took 4-34 as Israel slipped to 149 all out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Gibbons made 51 out of Bermuda's 217 against the Netherlands, who lost their last four wickets for 12 runs to lose by 30 runs (Lightbourne 4-44).
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Canada's openers Dipchand (105) and Prashad (129) shared an opening partnership of 233 as their country made 356/2; Fiji made 109 to lose by a mammoth 247 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Israel made a highly respectable 262 against Gibraltar, with Z Moshe making 77, Perlman 69 and S Nemblette 63, but P White's 5-48 for the Gibraltarians proved important; they won by three wickets with eight balls to spare thanks to five scores of between 35 and 49.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Hong Kong's 257/8 (Brian Catton 63, Ray Brewster) against Papua New Guinea looked good, but 55 from Vai and 50 from Maha was enough to get PNG home by two wickets with two overs in hand.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Bermuda batted first and fell to 41/3, but recovered somewhat to put up a reasonable total of 201/7 from their 60 overs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Gibbons held the innings together with 58, while number seven OW Jones added a useful unbeaten 35; Rawson (3-28) had the best bowling figures.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] In reply, however, Zimbabwe sailed to an ominously impressive ten-wicket triumph inside 39 overs, with Paterson cashing in for 123 not out while his batting partner Robin Brown reached 61 not out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Denmark were in difficulties at 62/4 early on against the Dutch, with Elferink claiming 3-28, but then a stand of 99 between J Morild (who was eventually run out for 86) and Henriksen (42) righted the ship and guided the Danes to 224/8.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The Netherlands also had their own problems and were 96/4 at one stage, but their scorecard was dominated by Gomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] He made 127 not out, 56.4% of his team's total, as they overhauled their target with five wickets and 5.4 overs still remaining.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Denmark won this consolation game easily.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Batting first the Bermudians put on an opening stand of 51, but struggled badly thereafter against Henriksen (4-26) and Mortensen (3-29), losing five wickets for 24 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] A partnership of 60 between captain Arnold Manders (45) and his namesake Andre (26) restored some respectability, but a further collapse followed with the last five wickets going down for 20 to leave Bermuda 155 all out.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Their bowlers had some early success as they reduced Denmark to 17/2 and 50/3, but A From-Hansen's timely innings of 78 made sure of a six-wicket victory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The Netherlands won the toss and put Zimbabwe in to bat.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The African team made 243/9 from their allotted overs, with Brown hitting 60 and future Test player Andy Waller 59.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Lubbers' 3-44 from 11 overs kept the total down to a gettable one, and the Netherlands had reached 11 without loss in reply when the rains came.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] On the reserve day, the Dutch went well at first to reach 109/1 before disaster struck with five wickets falling for 30 runs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] Lubbers and Elferink tried to repair the damage with a defiant stand of 67, but it was too late as Iain Butchart (4-33) mopped up the tail.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/1986-icc-trophy] The Netherlands were all out for 218, with eight balls still left in the innings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In May to October 1868, a cricket team composed of Aboriginal Australians toured England, becoming the first organised group of Australian sportspeople to travel overseas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] It would be another ten years before an Australian cricket team classed as representative left the country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The concept of an Aboriginal cricket team can be traced to pastoral stations in the Western District of Victoria, where, in the mid-1860s, the European owners introduced Aboriginal station hands to the sport.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] An Aboriginal XI was created with the assistance of Tom Wills, the captain of the Victorian cricket team and founder of Australian rules football, who acted as the side's captain-coach in the lead-up to and during an 1866–67 tour of Victoria and New South Wales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Several members of the team joined what became the Aboriginal XI that toured England under the captaincy of Englishman Charles Lawrence.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] International sporting contact was rare in that era.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Previously, only three cricket teams had travelled abroad, all English, to the United States and Canada in 1859, and to Australia in 1861–62 and 1863–64.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The 1850s and 1860s saw a rapid increase in the popularity of cricket in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In the Western District of Victoria, from the early 1860s onwards, cricket matches took place between Aboriginal Australians and European settlers at local pastoral properties, where many Aboriginal people were employed as station hands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The Aboriginal people were admired for their athletic skills and, in early 1866, a series of matches were staged with the intention of selecting the strongest possible Aboriginal XI.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Thomas Gibson Hamilton of Bringalbert Station, near Edenhope, created a team which he coached.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] They played an exhibition match at Hamilton, which gained the attention of Tom Wills.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The resulting team was initially coached by local pastoralist William Hayman.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Coaching duties were later turned over to Wills, captain of the Victoria cricket team and founder of Australian rules football, who spoke to the team in the Djab Wurrung language he had learnt as a child growing up in the Western District among the Djab Wurrung people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] To commentators at the time, Wills' decision to join and help the team was something of a puzzle given that, only five years earlier, he had survived the Cullin-la-ringo massacre in Queensland, in which his father and 18 other European colonists were murdered by local indigenous people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] "It was always a matter of wonder how Tom could be friendly with the blacks, considering that they murdered his father", one sportswriter noted.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] On Boxing Day 1866, in front of over 10,000 spectators, Wills captained the team against the Melbourne Cricket Club at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] "A dark skin suddenly became a passport to the good graces of Victorians." Although they lost to the MCC, the Aboriginal players were commended for their performance, and showed marked improvement on a subsequent tour of country Victoria.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] An entrepreneur, Captain Gurnett, persuaded the team to travel to Sydney to begin a planned tour of the colonies and England.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] However, after their arrival in Sydney in February 1867, Gurnett embezzled some of the funds raised to finance the enterprise, leaving the team stranded.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] They were looked after by Charles Lawrence at his Manly Hotel, and he organised a number of games, completing a tour of New South Wales before returning to Victoria in May.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Four players succumbed to the effects of illness: "Sugar" and "Watty" died on tour, while "Jellico" and "Paddy" died shortly afterward.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In 1867, Charles Lawrence was contracted to captain-coach Australia's "First Eleven" that toured England in 1868.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Lawrence played for Surrey in 1855, the all Ireland XI in 1862, and the all England XI in 1863.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] He was contracted to be the first professional cricket coach in New South Wales, and he first saw the indigenous team under the instructions of Tom Wills who played a match at the Albert Ground, Sydney.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] On this occasion there was some contract disagreement between the failed sponsor Gurnett and Wills, and the players were left in Sydney.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Lawrence was instructed to look after the Aboriginal players.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] At this time Lawrence was a publican and billeted the players in his hotel in Manly until he could arrange some cricket matches to raise money to return the players to the Western District of Victoria.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In 1867, he trained the players for two months at "Lake Wallace" in Edenhope in the Wimmera before selecting the below side to tour England in 1868.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Surrey County Cricket Club also supplied one of its ground staff (William Shepherd) to accompany the aboriginal tour as occasional relief player and umpire.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The tour was financed by Sydney Lawyer George Graham.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Along with his cousin George Smith (who had been Mayor of Sydney in 1859), and William Hayman, they all travelled to England for the tour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] During June, "King Cole" died from tuberculosis and was buried in Victoria Park Cemetery in what is now Tower Hamlets in London.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Sundown and Jim Crow went home in August due to ill-health.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] None of the Aboriginal players were paid for participating in the tour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Having played an exhibition match attended by Prince Alfred at the Albert Ground, the side departed Sydney aboard the *Parramatta* on 8 February 1868.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Arriving in Gravesend on 13 May, they spent time recovering from the journey in Town Malling before travelling to London.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] They were met with a degree of fascination – being the period of the evolutionary controversies following publication of Charles Darwin's *The Origin of Species* in 1859.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The first match was played on 25–26 May at the Oval in London, attracting 20,000 spectators.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Presumably many of the spectators attended out of curiosity, rather than merely to savour a cricket contest.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In total, the Aboriginal team played 47 matches throughout England over a period of six months, winning 14, losing 14 and drawing 19, a good result that surprised many at the time.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Their skills were said to range from individuals who were exceptional athletes down to two or three team members who hardly contributed at all.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The outstanding player was Johnny Mullagh.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] He scored 1,698 runs and took 245 wickets.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In addition to playing cricket, the Aboriginal players frequently put on exhibitions of boomerang and spear throwing at the conclusion of a match.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Dick-a-Dick would also hold a narrow parrying shield and invite people to throw cricket balls at him, which he warded off with the shield.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The Aboriginal team were narrowly beaten in a cricket-ball-throwing competition by an emerging English all-rounder of star quality, the 20-year-old W.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] On 16 October, members of Surrey County Cricket Club as well as the general public gathered in Canterbury Music Hall, London, where each of the touring cricketers was presented with a commemorative bat.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The team arrived back in Sydney in February 1869.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] They played a match against a military team the following month, then split up.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Twopenny later moved to New South Wales and played for the colony against Victoria in 1870.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Cuzens died of dysentery the following year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Mullagh was employed as a professional by the Melbourne Cricket Club and represented Victoria against the touring English team in 1879, top-scoring in the second innings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In 1869 the Central Board for Aborigines ruled that it would be illegal to remove any Aboriginal person from the colony of Victoria without the approval of the government minister.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] That effectively curtailed the involvement of Aboriginal players in the game.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] When Mullagh died in August 1891, aged 50, he was reported to be the last surviving member of the team other than Lawrence, who died in 1917.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] However, Red Cap is now believed to have died between 1891 and 1894, and Tarpot died in April 1900.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] William Shepherd wrote some observations about the players 51 years later, published in Ayres Cricket Companion in the year of his death, 1919.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] On 13 October 1951, former Australia captain Vic Richardson unveiled a memorial to the side in Edenhope, Victoria, where the players had trained prior to the tour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In May 1988, an Aboriginal team captained by John McGuire visited England to mark the Australian Bicentenary, retracing the steps of the 1868 side.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Vince Copley of the Ngadjuri people assisted in organising the tour, about which a documentary entitled Dreaming of Lords was shown the following year on Channel 4 in the United Kingdom.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In 2002, Charles Lawrence's great-great-grandson, Ian Friend, along with historians and cricketers, including former Test captain Ian Chappell, successfully campaigned to have the Aboriginal XI recognised in the Sport Australia Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Ian Friend and Jack Kennedy (descendant of Johnny Cuzens) both accepted the award on behalf of the team.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Also that year, a documentary film about the team, titled *A Fine Body of Gentlemen*, was broadcast by the ABC.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Australia sent men's and women's Aboriginal teams to England in June 2018, to mark the 150th anniversary of the tour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In December 2019, Cricket Australia revealed plans for the Johnny Mullagh Medal, to be awarded to the best player in the Boxing Day Test match from 2020.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] The medal is a recreation of the belt buckle he wore with the addition of a picture of the 1868 team.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] A play about the cricketers, *Black Cockatoo*, written by Geoffrey Atherden and employing an all-Aboriginal cast, was staged at the 2020 Sydney Festival.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] In January 2020, Len Pascoe encouraged singer/songwriter Matt Scullion to write a song about the tour, having been talking about it to Gamilaraay elder and retired cricketer Les Knox.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] Scullion wrote the song, "1868", and sang it at the second Twenty20 International at the Sydney Cricket Ground in early 2021, and planned to do so again at the Bradman Museum in April 2021.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] A number of Aboriginal artefacts brought to England by the tour party are preserved in the collection of the Royal Albert Memorial Museum in Exeter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868/australian-aboriginal-cricket-team-in-england-in-1868] A club used by Dick-a-Dick is also in the possession of the Marylebone Cricket Club.
